<h1>1. Business Plan: Maintenance & Monitoring System (MMS)</h1>

<h2>Executive Summary</h2>
<p>The Maintenance & Monitoring System (MMS) is a centralized, cloud-based platform designed for educational institutions, specifically tailored for Baliuag University. It streamlines the reporting, tracking, and resolution of facility issues (electrical, plumbing, IT, carpentry). By replacing outdated paper-based requests with a digital ticketing system equipped with real-time analytics, MMS significantly reduces response times, ensures accountability, and provides administrators with data-driven insights to maintain a high-quality learning environment.</p>

<h2>Business Description (Vision, Mission, Goals)</h2>
<p><b>Vision:</b> To be the leading digital infrastructure management solution for educational institutions, ensuring safe, efficient, and well-maintained learning environments.</p>
<p><b>Mission:</b> To provide a seamless, user-friendly platform that connects students, faculty, and maintenance staff, enabling rapid response and proactive facility management through real-time data and tracking.</p>
<p><b>Goals:</b></p>
<ul>
<li>Digitize 100% of maintenance requests within the first 6 months of deployment.</li>
<li>Reduce average issue response time by 40%.</li>
<li>Provide transparent tracking for users and actionable analytics for administration.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Problem Statement / Opportunity</h2>
<p><b>The Problem:</b> Currently, reporting broken facilities (e.g., busted lights, broken chairs, network outages) relies on inefficient verbal communication or paper forms. This leads to lost requests, delayed repairs, lack of accountability, and frustration among students and staff. Administrators have no clear oversight of maintenance performance or recurring facility issues.</p>
<p><b>The Opportunity:</b> By introducing a digital ticketing portal, MMS capitalizes on the university's need for operational efficiency. It creates a centralized hub that saves time, prevents resource wastage, and improves the overall campus experience.</p>

<h2>Product/Service Description (Tech-based solution)</h2>
<p>MMS is a web-based application offering a dual-interface system:</p>
<ul>
<li><b>User Portal (Students/Faculty):</b> Allows users to quickly submit issue reports (tickets) with specific categories, locations, priority levels, and optional photo/video attachments. Users can track the real-time status of their own tickets.</li>
<li><b>Admin Dashboard (Maintenance Dept.):</b> A comprehensive control center featuring live data analytics, search/filtering capabilities, and one-click ticket resolution tracking.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Market Analysis (Target users, competitors)</h2>
<p><b>Target Users:</b></p>
<ul>
<li><i>Primary Users:</i> University students, professors, and department staff who encounter facility issues.</li>
<li><i>Primary Customers (B2B):</i> University administration and the General Services/Maintenance Department who will purchase and implement the system.</li>
</ul>
<p><b>Competitors:</b></p>
<ul>
<li>Traditional methods (paper forms, phone calls).</li>
<li>Generic ticketing tools (Zendesk, Jira) which are often too expensive, overly complex, and not tailored specifically for local university environments. MMS stands out by being highly customized, affordable, and focused purely on campus infrastructure.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Marketing Strategy (4Ps)</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>Product:</b> A highly customized, university-branded web application with mobile-responsive design for easy on-the-go reporting.</li>
<li><b>Price:</b> Subscription-based Software-as-a-Service (SaaS) model. A tiered pricing structure based on campus size (e.g., Basic tier for single campuses, Premium for multi-campus institutions).</li>
<li><b>Place:</b> Cloud-hosted (e.g., Vercel/AWS), accessible globally via any modern web browser without needing to download a native app.</li>
<li><b>Promotion:</b> Direct B2B sales presentations to university administrators, free trial periods for the General Services department, and student awareness campaigns (posters/social media) to encourage adoption.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Operations Plan</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>Workflow:</b>
  <ol>
  <li>User identifies an issue and submits a ticket via MMS.</li>
  <li>System logs ticket and updates Admin analytics.</li>
  <li>Admin assigns maintenance staff to the location based on priority.</li>
  <li>Once fixed, Admin marks the ticket as "Resolved", triggering a notification to the user.</li>
  </ol>
</li>
<li><b>Tools Used:</b> HTML5, CSS3 (Custom Glassmorphism UI), Vanilla JavaScript (ES6+), LocalStorage (for MVP), Chart.js (Analytics), Vercel (Hosting).</li>
<li><b>System Architecture:</b> Client-side rendered web app interacting with a cloud database to handle authentication, ticket CRUD operations, and data aggregation.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Financial Plan</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>Costs (Estimated):</b>
  <ul>
  <li>Development & Maintenance: ₱50,000/year</li>
  <li>Cloud Hosting & Domain (AWS/Vercel): ₱10,000/year</li>
  <li>Marketing & Sales: ₱15,000/year</li>
  </ul>
</li>
<li><b>Pricing:</b> ₱10,000/month per university campus (Annual contract: ₱100,000/year with a 2-month discount).</li>
<li><b>Projected Income:</b> Securing just 3 university clients in Year 1 yields ₱300,000 revenue. Gross Profit: ₱225,000 (75% margin).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Risk Analysis and Sustainability Plan</h2>
<ul>
<li><b>Risk 1: Low User Adoption.</b> <i>Mitigation:</i> Conduct campus-wide orientation and place QR codes in classrooms directly linking to the report form.</li>
<li><b>Risk 2: Server Downtime.</b> <i>Mitigation:</i> Utilize reliable cloud hosting with 99.9% uptime guarantees and automated daily database backups.</li>
<li><b>Sustainability Plan:</b> To ensure long-term viability, MMS will continuously collect feedback via the User Validation Report to release iterative updates. Future plans include expanding the system to cover inventory management for maintenance supplies.</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h1>2. Technical Documentation</h1>

<h2>System Architecture</h2>
<p>The architecture follows a standard client-server model. For the MVP, the browser's LocalStorage acts as the mock database, but the architecture is designed to seamlessly integrate a backend API (like Firebase or Node.js) in the future. The Frontend Web App is built using HTML/CSS/JS and is hosted on Vercel. Both User and Admin devices access the app via the Internet.</p>

<h2>Tools & Technologies Used</h2>
<table>
  <tr>
    <th>Category</th>
    <th>Technology Used</th>
    <th>Purpose in the System</th>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Structure</td>
    <td>HTML5</td>
    <td>Creates the semantic layout and forms of the login and dashboard pages.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Styling</td>
    <td>Vanilla CSS3 (Custom)</td>
    <td>Implements the responsive design, glassmorphism UI, custom university colors (Green & Gold), and hover animations.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Logic & Interactivity</td>
    <td>Vanilla JavaScript (ES6+)</td>
    <td>Handles form submission, modal popups, dynamic DOM manipulation, and Admin/User role authentication logic.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Data Storage</td>
    <td>Web Storage API (LocalStorage)</td>
    <td>Simulates a cloud database for the MVP, securely saving JSON-stringified tickets locally in the browser.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Data Visualization</td>
    <td>Chart.js (via CDN)</td>
    <td>Renders the dynamic, animated pie chart on the Admin dashboard based on real ticket status counts.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Hosting & Deployment</td>
    <td>Vercel</td>
    <td>Automatically builds and hosts the live website securely via HTTPS directly from the GitHub repository.</td>
  </tr>
</table>

